Docker Overview
What is Docker?
Docker is a platform for packaging and running applications in containers — isolated, lightweight processes that bundle an app with all its dependencies.

Containers vs VMs
Feature	Container	VM
Isolation	Process-level (shares OS kernel)	Full OS isolation
Size	MBs	GBs
Startup	Milliseconds	Seconds–minutes
Overhead	Very low	High
Portability	High	Moderate

┌─────────────────────┐    ┌─────────────────────┐
│  App A  │  App B    │    │  App A   │  App B    │
│ [Libs]  │ [Libs]    │    │ Guest OS │ Guest OS  │
├─────────┴───────────┤    ├──────────┴───────────┤
│    Docker Engine    │    │     Hypervisor        │
├─────────────────────┤    ├───────────────────────┤
│      Host OS        │    │       Host OS         │
└─────────────────────┘    └───────────────────────┘
        Containers                   VMs

Install Docker (Linux)
# Install via convenience script
curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com | sh

# Add your user to the docker group (avoid sudo)
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker

Key Commands
# Pull and run the hello-world image
docker run hello-world

# List running containers
docker ps

# List ALL containers (including stopped)
docker ps -a

# List downloaded images
docker images

Sample output of docker ps:
CONTAINER ID   IMAGE     COMMAND   CREATED   STATUS    PORTS   NAMES

Sample output of docker images:
