hello-world   latest    d2c94e258dcb   13 months ago  13.3kB

Core Concepts
Image — read-only template (the blueprint)
Container — a running instance of an image
Registry — image storage hub (e.g., Docker Hub at hub.docker.com)
Dockerfile — script to build a custom image

Docker Hands-On Practice — Step by Step
Phase 1: Setup & First Container
# 1. Verify installation
docker --version
docker info

# 2. Run hello-world
docker run hello-world

# 3. Observe what happened — Docker pulled image, created container, ran it, exited
docker ps -a          # see the stopped hello-world container
docker images         # see the hello-world image cached locally

Phase 2: Interactive Containers
# 4. Run Ubuntu interactively
docker run -it ubuntu bash

# Inside the container:
whoami                # root
hostname              # container ID
ls /
cat /etc/os-release
exit

# 5. Back on host — container is stopped
docker ps -a

Phase 3: Container Lifecycle
# 6. Run a named container in background (detached)
docker run -d --name mybox alpine sleep 300

# 7. Check it's running
docker ps

# 8. Execute a command inside running container
docker exec -it mybox sh
ls
exit

# 9. Stop, start, remove
docker stop mybox
docker start mybox
docker rm -f mybox

Phase 4: Port Mapping
# 10. Run nginx web server, map host:8080 → container:80
docker run -d --name webserver -p 8080:80 nginx

# 11. Test it
curl http://localhost:8080
# or open browser at localhost:8080

docker logs webserver        # view logs
docker stop webserver
docker rm webserver

Phase 5: Volume (Persist Data)
# 12. Run nginx with a custom HTML page via bind mount
mkdir ~/mysite
echo "<h1>Hello from Docker!</h1>" > ~/mysite/index.html

docker run -d --name mysite \
  -p 8080:80 \
  -v ~/mysite:/usr/share/nginx/html \
  nginx

curl http://localhost:8080   # see your custom page

# Edit the file on host — change reflects immediately in container
echo "<h1>Updated!</h1>" > ~/mysite/index.html
curl http://localhost:8080

Phase 6: Build Your Own Image
# 13. Create a Dockerfile
mkdir ~/myapp && cd ~/myapp
cat > Dockerfile <<EOF
FROM python:3.11-slim
WORKDIR /app
COPY app.py .
CMD ["python", "app.py"]
EOF

cat > app.py <<EOF
print("Hello from my Docker image!")
EOF

# 14. Build and run
docker build -t myapp:v1 .
docker run myapp:v1

# 15. Inspect image layers
docker history myapp:v1
docker inspect myapp:v1

Phase 7: Cleanup
# Remove stopped containers
docker container prune

# Remove unused images
docker image prune

# Remove everything unused
docker system prune -a

# Remove everything unused
docker system prune -aInterview Questions & Answers
Conceptual
Q1. What is Docker and why is it used?

Docker packages apps + dependencies into containers ensuring "works on my machine" = works everywhere. Used for consistent dev/test/prod environments, microservices, CI/CD.

Q2. Difference between Container and VM?

Containers share the host OS kernel, are lightweight (MBs, ms startup). VMs have a full guest OS, are heavy (GBs, minutes startup). Containers are not full isolation — they share kernel.

Q3. What is a Docker Image vs Container?

Image = read-only blueprint (like a class). Container = running instance of an image (like an object). Multiple containers can run from one image.

Q4. What is a Dockerfile?

A text script with instructions (FROM, RUN, COPY, CMD, etc.) to build a Docker image layer by layer.

Q5. What is Docker Hub?

A public registry to store and share Docker images. Like GitHub but for images.

Command-Based
Q6. How do you see only running containers?

docker ps

Q7. How do you see all containers including stopped?

docker ps -a

Q8. How do you run a container in background?

docker run -d image_name

Q9. How do you get a shell inside a running container?

docker exec -it <container_id> bash

Q10. How do you map port 8080 on host to 80 in container?

docker run -p 8080:80 nginx

Q11. Difference between docker stop and docker kill?

stop sends SIGTERM (graceful shutdown). kill sends SIGKILL (immediate termination).

Q12. How do you remove an image?

docker rmi image_name — must stop/remove containers using it first.

Advanced Scenario
Q13. What happens when you run docker run hello-world?

Docker checks local images — not found
Pulls hello-world from Docker Hub
Creates a container from the image
Runs the container — prints message
Container exits (status: Exited)
Q14. What is a dangling image?

An untagged image (<none>:<none>) left behind after rebuilding. Removed with docker image prune.

Q15. How do you persist data beyond a container's life?

Use volumes (docker volume) or bind mounts (-v /host/path:/container/path).

Q16. What is the difference between COPY and ADD in Dockerfile?

COPY copies local files only. ADD can also extract tar files and fetch from URLs — prefer COPY unless you need those extras.

Q17. What does docker system prune do?

Removes all stopped containers, dangling images, unused networks, and build cache.

